    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1780659303" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1780659303" />
    <a title=" Li&#39;l Owl" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/48372551-li-l-owl"><img alt=" Li&#39;l Owl" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1616729152p2/48372551.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1780659303?book_show_action=true">Oct 10, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title=" Li&#39;l Owl" class="user" itemprop="url" name=" Li&#39;l Owl" href="/user/show/48372551-li-l-owl"> Li&#39;l Owl</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48372551-li-l-owl?shelf=psychological-suspense-thriller">psychological-suspense-thriller</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48372551-li-l-owl?shelf=series">series</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48372551-li-l-owl?shelf=owl-s-favorite-audiobooks">owl-s-favorite-audiobooks</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48372551-li-l-owl?shelf=debut-novel">debut-novel</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48372551-li-l-owl?shelf=uk-author-setting">uk-author-setting</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48372551-li-l-owl?shelf=owl-s-favorite-books-authors">owl-s-favorite-books-authors</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48372551-li-l-owl?shelf=owl-s-favorite-narrators">owl-s-favorite-narrators</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48372551-li-l-owl?shelf=owl-s-audible-audiobooks-own">owl-s-audible-audiobooks-own</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48372551-li-l-owl?shelf=detective-police-procedural-sheriff">detective-police-procedural-sheriff</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/48372551-li-l-owl?shelf=award-winning-book-author">award-winning-book-author</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1780659303" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15115064077761311605"><b>
  <i>&quot;In the UK, a child is reported missing every three minutes. <br/><a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='http://www.missingkids.co.uk'>www.missingkids.co.uk</a><br/>The first three hours are the most critical when trying to locate a missing child.<br/><a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='http://www.missingkids/keyfacts'>www.missingkids/keyfacts</a>&quot;</i>
</b><br/> <br/>On a beautiful autumn afternoon in October Rachel Jenner and her eight year old son, Ben, went for a walk in Bristol park woods. Ben, in a red anorak jacket, running alongside his mum with his dog, a black and white Cocker Spaniel named Skittle. The afternoon was getting late, the cold had started to bite</span>
  <span id="freeText15115064077761311605" style="display:none"><b>
  <i>"In the UK, a child is reported missing every three minutes. <br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.missingkids.co.uk">www.missingkids.co.uk</a><br />The first three hours are the most critical when trying to locate a missing child.<br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://www.missingkids/keyfacts">www.missingkids/keyfacts</a>&quot;</i>
</b><br /> <br />On a beautiful autumn afternoon in October Rachel Jenner and her eight year old son, Ben, went for a walk in Bristol park woods. Ben, in a red anorak jacket, running alongside his mum with his dog, a black and white Cocker Spaniel named Skittle. The afternoon was getting late, the cold had started to bite and Rachel wants to return to the car. Ben had other ideas. He wanted to go for a ride on the rope swing before leaving. He begs his mum, the way kids do, if he can run on ahead to the swing, insisting that he knows the way. After an internal tug of war between being the cautious mum and the "let the boy have a bit of independence" voice, Rachel relents. And so, she watches as Ben and Skittle disappear happily into the woods. <br />That was the last time Rachel saw her son. <br />And so it begins....... <br /><br />There are two separate storylines in this audiobook which run side by side throughout, but are easily discernible so it's not confusing or overwhelming. <br /><br />The first storyline chronicles the search for Ben at the time it happened as seen from two perspectives. One comes from Ben's mother, Rachel, as she struggles with the disappearance of her son as the days unfold. The second is from the viewpoint of lead detective, DI James Clemo, as he gets his first chance at a big, high profile case. <br /><br />As is usually the case, there are many possible suspects who could have taken Ben. Family members are always the ones who must be looked at very carefully as this is statistically significant. Among them is Ben's father, John, Rachel's now ex-husband, who left Rachel ten months before for his new wife Katrina, whom he was having an affair prior to the divorce. Then, DI Clemo uncovers a secret that Rachel's sister, Nikki, that could change the course of the investigation into a whole new direction. <br /><br />Strangers in the media and the public have made up their own minds about Rachel. The majority consensus being that she's done something to harm Ben. A blog has been started titled <i>
  <b>"Where is Benedict Finch? For the curious... </b>
</i> by someone calling themselves "Lazy Donkey", mostly saying that "the mother" is guilty, persecuting Rachel with innuendo and rumors, with few facts. Most people jump on board with Mr. Donkey, (which is a perfect "cleaned up" name for this unsavory character, if you follow my meaning.)<br />Only a few people are making clear their distaste towards "Lazy Donkey" and to those who've already found her guilty by speaking out and fighting back for Rachel, posting supportive words and prayers for strength and hope that Ben will be found safe and returned to his mother where he belongs. <br />I have to admit that I was in the minority believing that Rachel had nothing to do with Ben's disappearance other than being a mother in a world where tragedy can strike indiscriminately, anytime, anywhere, to anyone. But of course, I couldn't know the truth. Not yet anyway. <br /><br />As the search for Ben continues, a second storyline emerges set in DI "Jim" Clemo's future, after the case comes to an end.<br />The Benedict Finch case left Jim tormented by nightmares, anxiety, and severe emotional distress. He is required by the department to have counselling sessions with psychologist, Francesa Menalli. We follow Jim as he reluctantly agrees to see Dr. Menalli mostly because he can't return to work as a detective until the psychological evaluation is complete. Jim is a strong character, proud and unwilling to show emotion as he sees it as a weakness. From day one, Jim is closed, guarded, making this clear to Dr. Menalli that this will be a difficult nut to crack. But she is an expert, slowly and carefully chipping away at Jim's hard exterior. <br /><br />This is a debut novel by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/8183303.Gilly_Macmillan" title="Gilly Macmillan" rel="nofollow noopener">Gilly Macmillan</a> which I had forgotten as the book is so deftly and cleverly crafted. <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25817531.What_She_Knew__Jim_Clemo__1_" title="What She Knew (Jim Clemo #1) by Gilly Macmillan" rel="nofollow noopener">What She Knew</a> has many moving pieces within multiple storylines, changes in perspective, complex characters, and going back and forth from the time of the search to Jim's emotional response afterwards. Yet, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/8183303.Gilly_Macmillan" title="Gilly Macmillan" rel="nofollow noopener">Gilly Macmillan</a> pulls it off beautifully. It's expertly woven together without becoming a confusing jumbled up mess. In fact it was quite the opposite, flowing quickly and easily, without becoming bogged down even with factual information mixed in. The story is captivating, gripping, spun with twists and turns, and chock full of intriguing details that go along with an investigation into one of the most intense types of crime. <br />A missing child.<br /><br />I especially enjoyed all the factual website pages of information about missing children added to fiction including a site <i>"When your child is missing. A family survival guide, missing kids parental guide USA US department of justice."</i> as it gives it a fresh, unique, and interesting true crime feel. I'm excited to see what she has in store for us in her future novels. <br /><br />There are two narrators for this audiobook who are firmly on my favorite list. <br /><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/14817662.Penelope_Rawlings" title="Penelope Rawlings" rel="nofollow noopener">Penelope Rawlings</a> narration is seemingly effortless as she enhanced each of Gilly Macmillan's beautifully detailed characters with voices that fitted each individual perfectly, giving them life and palpable emotions that you can feel as you listen. The voices for Rachel, Ben, Nikki, and Ruth were my favorites. <br /><a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/14416414.Dugald_Bruce_Lockhart" title="Dugald Bruce-Lockhart" rel="nofollow noopener">Dugald Bruce-Lockhart</a> brought life to DI Jim Clemo, investigators, and Dr. Francesa Menalli. He, too, put an individual and distinct voice to each character he narrated, portraying each person brilliantly, just as I believe author,<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/8183303.Gilly_Macmillan" title="Gilly Macmillan" rel="nofollow noopener">Gilly Macmillan</a>, intended each one to be.<br /><br /><br />As I said, this second time I've listened to this audiobook. The first time was almost two years ago and I loved it very much. So much so that it stayed in my mind, resurfacing every now and then. Strangely enough, I didn't remember how it ended. Perhaps my mind chose not to remember because it wanted to revisit the story again. And so, when I discovered the second DI James Clemo novel, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/34150785.Odd_Child_Out__Jim_Clemo__2_" title="Odd Child Out (Jim Clemo #2) by Gilly Macmillan" rel="nofollow noopener">Odd Child Out</a>, I decided to listen to <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/25817531.What_She_Knew__Jim_Clemo__1_" title="What She Knew (Jim Clemo #1) by Gilly Macmillan" rel="nofollow noopener">What She Knew</a> for a second time and I was not disapointed! I loved it all over again! From the moment I started listening, I became absorbed in it. I found myself sneaking in every opportunity to listen as the search went on. The nearer I got to the conclusion the more breathless I became, my heart knocking against my ribs with raw anticipation. <br /><br />I can say without hesitation that this novel is a must read! I highly recommend the audio version as you won't be bothered by having to turn the pages!<br /><br /><b>
  <u>Review from first time listening.</u>
</b><br />I listened to this audio book before I added all my books to GR so it didn't get reviewed. Even though I heard this over a year ago I still remember how I was totally absorbed in the story! That tells me that I really loved it as I can actually remember, not just the book title, but the story as well. I honestly don't remember what happened at the end at the moment but, irrregardless, there's a strong possibility that I will listen to it again as I just purchased the second in the <i>Jim Clemo</i> series, <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/34150785.Odd_Child_Out__Jim_Clemo__2_" title="Odd Child Out (Jim Clemo #2) by Gilly Macmillan" rel="nofollow noopener">Odd Child Out</a>.<br /> <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/14817662.Penelope_Rawlings" title="Penelope Rawlings" rel="nofollow noopener">Penelope Rawlings</a> was the narrator for the the missing boy's mother, Rachel Jenner. The main character, DI Jim Clemo, was narrated by <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/14416414.Dugald_Bruce_Lockhart" title="Dugald Bruce-Lockhart" rel="nofollow noopener">Dugald Bruce-Lockhart</a>. I really enjoyed two separate narrators which was a first for me<br />and both did an excellent job bringing the characters to life.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15115064077761311605" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


