<div id="review_3238717727" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3238717727" />
    <a title="Karina" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/62428250-karina"><img alt="Karina" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1632727821p2/62428250.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3238717727?book_show_action=true">Mar 23, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Karina" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Karina" href="/user/show/62428250-karina">Karina</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3238717727" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7578777705685514908">Day 7 of Benedict Finch gone missing<br/><br/>&quot;An abduction may occur for many reasons, including a desire to possess a child, sexual gratification, financial gain, and the desire to kill.... Moreover, child homicide usually follows an abduction and is not the reason for the abduction.&quot; -- Marlene L. Dalley and Jenna Ruscoe, &quot;The Abduction by Strangers in Canada and Scope,&quot; National Missing Children&apos;s Services, National Police Services, Royal Canadian Mounted Police, December 2003 (page 289)<br/><br/>3.5 This was a</span>
  <span id="freeText7578777705685514908" style="display:none">Day 7 of Benedict Finch gone missing<br /><br />"An abduction may occur for many reasons, including a desire to possess a child, sexual gratification, financial gain, and the desire to kill.... Moreover, child homicide usually follows an abduction and is not the reason for the abduction." -- Marlene L. Dalley and Jenna Ruscoe, "The Abduction by Strangers in Canada and Scope," National Missing Children's Services, National Police Services, Royal Canadian Mounted Police, December 2003 (page 289)<br /><br />3.5 This was a pretty good thriller and I never guessed who it was. The author didn't leave many clues until past the middle, which to be honest, was annoying me. It wouldn't get to the plot. The characters kept saying the same things over and over. Some of the betrayals were unexpected so they were a welcome addition to the plot. The story felt too long. 470 pages could have been cut down to 370 pages instead and it would have made a better more compact story. I will say it was NOT gory or full of despicable descriptions. It was in the mother's and the detective's alternating point of views. <br /><br />The things the mother went through with the media and the online social commentary broke my heart. She was part of a criticism she could not escape. Rachel tried to give her 8 yr-old son a bit of independence by letting him run ahead of her to the swings in the woods with his dog and it ended up being the worst, most regretted mistake she ever did and was persecuted for it. How many times have you let your kids run off or play in the front yard for less than 5 minutes before you were checking in on them? How can we know that no one is stalking our movements to catch us off guard? Being a parent is hard and the outside world doesn't make it easy.<br /><br /> I remember being a "street kid" and having to run inside once the street lights turned on; riding my bike anywhere, everywhere as long as I wasn't in my mom's way. Now I can't kick out the kids because I have to worry and then I'm worried because we are not out and they will get chunky playing on stupid tablets or watching TV while snacking.... Where does it end? LOL</span>
  <a data-text-id="7578777705685514908" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


